Given, ABCD is a parallelogram. AC and BD are two diagonals of it. We have to express the vectors \vec{AB} and \vec{AC} in terms of \vec{AD} and \vec{BD} and have to show that,
\vec{AC} + \vec{BD} = 2\vec{BC} \text{ and } \vec{AC} - \vec{BD} = 2\vec{AB}.

\text{In the triangle } \Delta ABD,
\vec{AD} = \vec{AB} + \vec{BD} \text{ [triangle law]}
\therefore \vec{AB} = \vec{AD} - \vec{BD} \text{.............(i)}
\text{Again in triangle ACD, } \vec{AC} = \vec{AD} + \vec{DC} \text{[triangle law]}
\text{[since, ABCD is parallelogram, so } \vec{DC} = \vec{AB}]
= \vec{AD} + \vec{AD} - \vec{BD} [\because \vec{AB} = \vec{AD} - \vec{BD}]
\therefore \vec{AC} = 2\vec{AD} - \vec{BD} \text{.............(ii)}
\text{Now, } \vec{AC} + \vec{BD} = 2\vec{AD} - \vec{BD} + \vec{BD}
\text{[adding } \vec{BD} \text{ in both sides of (ii)]}
= 2 \vec{AD}
\therefore \vec{AC} + \vec{BD} = 2 \vec{BC} \text{.............(iii)}
\text{[since, ABCD is parallelogram, so } \vec{AD} = \vec{BC}]
\text{Again, } \vec{AC} - \vec{BD} = (2\vec{AD} - \vec{BD}) - \vec{BD} \text{ [By using (ii)]}
= 2\vec{AD} - 2 \vec{BD} = 2 (\vec{AD} - \vec{BD})
= 2\vec{AB} \text{ [By using (i)]}
\therefore \vec{AC} - \vec{BD} = 2\vec{AB} \text{.............(iv)}
\text{Now, from the equations (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv) we get,}
\vec{AB} = \vec{AD} - \vec{BD}
\vec{AC} = 2\vec{AD} - \vec{BD}
\vec{AC} + \vec{BD} = 2\vec{BC} \text{ and } \vec{AC} - \vec{BD} = 2\vec{AB} \text{ (Shown)}

